00:19:40,350 --> 00:19:41,797
why did this actually happen?

532
00:19:41,797 --> 00:19:43,080
"Was this a good thing?"

533
00:19:43,080 --> 00:19:45,780
Maybe you spend 24 hours
looking at an anomaly

534
00:19:45,780 --> 00:19:47,767
and realize, "Well, we were
in the front of a tech crunch,

535
00:19:47,767 --> 00:19:49,237
"and this is not a bad thing at all.

536
00:19:49,237 --> 00:19:50,257
"The cost should be going up

537
00:19:50,257 --> 00:19:52,770
"because we're scaling automatically."

538
00:19:52,770 --> 00:19:54,600
Maybe you had a great
quarter and all of a sudden

539
00:19:54,600 --> 00:19:56,760
you're doing a lot of quant calculations

540
00:19:56,760 --> 00:19:58,470
because you're making a lot of revenue.

541
00:19:58,470 --> 00:20:00,240
Well, of course the cost is gonna go up,

542
00:20:00,240 --> 00:20:02,520
but without that context
of why it's happening

543
00:20:02,520 --> 00:20:04,950
is really difficult, and
oftentimes what I've found

544
00:20:04,950 --> 00:20:07,170
is that engineers will get this alert,

545
00:20:07,170 --> 00:20:09,390
might be product or might be whoever,

546
00:20:09,390 --> 00:20:12,060
and as soon as they see,
"Well, this was a false alarm,"

547
00:20:12,060 --> 00:20:14,850
even if the limits are set
to say reasonable numbers,

548
00:20:14,850 --> 00:20:17,760
like only if the cost goes
up $100,000, alert me.

549
00:20:17,760 --> 00:20:19,770
If it was a good thing
and not a bad thing,

550
00:20:19,770 --> 00:20:21,150
you're gonna start ignoring it.

551
00:20:21,150 --> 00:20:22,980
And oftentimes when you
start ignoring these things

552
00:20:22,980 --> 00:20:24,240
is when the real problems arise

553
00:20:24,240 --> 00:20:27,490
because you kinda ignore the
actual issue when it happens

554
00:20:27,490 --> 00:20:29,490
because every single
time you've taken a look,

555
00:20:29,490 --> 00:20:32,430
it just feels like it's
another thing to ignore.

556
00:20:32,430 --> 00:20:34,320
So being able to fix these things,

557
00:20:34,320 --> 00:20:35,870
to me, comes down to this.

558
00:20:35,870 --> 00:20:38,700
It's very similar to security in a way.

559
00:20:38,700 --> 00:20:40,920
You wanna prevent the
bad things from happening

560
00:20:40,920 --> 00:20:42,180
first and foremost.

561
00:20:42,180 --> 00:20:46,230
In FinOps, it might be
that you wanna prevent

562
00:20:46,230 --> 00:20:47,640
in your ephemeral environments

563
00:20:47,640 --> 00:20:49,740
anything but spot instances.

564
00:20:49,740 --> 00:20:52,530
It might be that the Gen
AI team is the only one

565
00:20:52,530 --> 00:20:55,270
that should use the P5
clusters in Kubernetes

566
00:20:55,270 --> 00:20:57,750
'cause it's $95 an hour or whatever,

567
00:20:57,750 --> 00:20:59,970
and you don't want anyone
else to touch them.

568
00:20:59,970 --> 00:21:03,030
Or it might be on and on,
all these different rules

569
00:21:03,030 --> 00:21:05,010
that you wanna set in place that are,

570
00:21:05,010 --> 00:21:07,050
at the same time, not too restrictive

571
00:21:07,050 --> 00:21:09,120
where you're blocking
innovation in your teams,

572
00:21:09,120 --> 00:21:11,487
but also not so brittle
that every single time

573
00:21:11,487 --> 00:21:14,550
you set a policy in place,
an engineer comes to you

574
00:21:14,550 --> 00:21:16,770
and everything's an
exception all the time.

