00:21:16,770 --> 00:21:18,690
Eventually, if you start doing that,

576
00:21:18,690 --> 00:21:21,120
the teams will basically
just raise an exception

577
00:21:21,120 --> 00:21:22,680
for everything they wanna do,

578
00:21:22,680 --> 00:21:25,830
and this entire prevention
system that we've built

579
00:21:25,830 --> 00:21:27,303
kinda goes out the window.

580
00:21:28,470 --> 00:21:31,830
The second step is, if
you find you can prevent

581
00:21:31,830 --> 00:21:34,260
a lot of these things from happening,

582
00:21:34,260 --> 00:21:35,093
they'll still happen.

583
00:21:35,093 --> 00:21:37,470
There'll still be rules that were slipped

584
00:21:37,470 --> 00:21:40,410
or someone went in console
in your non-prod environment,

585
00:21:40,410 --> 00:21:43,350
did one small thing
that now raised the bar,

586
00:21:43,350 --> 00:21:44,970
or raised the price, rather.

587
00:21:44,970 --> 00:21:45,990
And when those things happen,

588
00:21:45,990 --> 00:21:48,120
you wanna detect them as soon as possible.

589
00:21:48,120 --> 00:21:49,710
And you wanna detect them not at the level

590
00:21:49,710 --> 00:21:51,990
of just only cost, which we're used to,

591
00:21:51,990 --> 00:21:54,150
but you wanna detect the
underlying reason for it.

592
00:21:54,150 --> 00:21:57,240
It might be that the thing
that someone was trying,

593
00:21:57,240 --> 00:21:59,490
they forgot to quote-unquote
shut off the lights.

594
00:21:59,490 --> 00:22:02,460
It was a experiment they
were running on inference

595
00:22:02,460 --> 00:22:04,560
or training a model, and afterward,

596
00:22:04,560 --> 00:22:06,990
they forgot to right-size
the cluster right after.

597
00:22:06,990 --> 00:22:08,430
It might be they're
doing performance testing

598
00:22:08,430 --> 00:22:11,550
and 24 hours later, the
performance test is done,

599
00:22:11,550 --> 00:22:12,900
but six months later, as you discover,

600
00:22:12,900 --> 00:22:14,050
this cluster's still running there.

601
00:22:14,050 --> 00:22:19,050
Or as a personal example,
once I had a call

602
00:22:19,770 --> 00:22:21,637
from AWS partners where they said,

603
00:22:21,637 --> 00:22:23,830
"This account that runs only $400 a month

604
00:22:23,830 --> 00:22:27,150
"is up to $180,000 in 24 hours."

605
00:22:27,150 --> 00:22:28,357
And we started looking, and we're like,

606
00:22:28,357 --> 00:22:29,610
"Oh God, what happened?"

607
00:22:29,610 --> 00:22:31,230
The oops moment.

608
00:22:31,230 --> 00:22:32,850
And it turns out someone was trying

609
00:22:32,850 --> 00:22:34,830
to do exponential back-off on queues,

610
00:22:34,830 --> 00:22:36,570
and they were using serverless, Lambdas,

611
00:22:36,570 --> 00:22:37,770
and so it should be really cheap,

612
00:22:37,770 --> 00:22:39,030
except they didn't really implement

613
00:22:39,030 --> 00:22:41,280
the exponential part properly.

614
00:22:41,280 --> 00:22:42,960
So we're retrying the same failed message

615
00:22:42,960 --> 00:22:45,720
600 times a second for 24 hours.

616
00:22:45,720 --> 00:22:46,657
And all of a sudden, you realize,

617
00:22:46,657 --> 00:22:49,117
"Well, why did we not know
about this immediately?

618
00:22:49,117 --> 00:22:52,447
"Why did we have to wait
until either getting a call

619
00:22:52,447 --> 00:22:55,057
"or an anomaly seven or eight hours later?

620
00:22:55,057 --> 00:22:57,157
"And oftentimes, when
you get this anomaly,

621
00:22:57,157 --> 00:22:58,807
"why was it not told me immediately

622
00:22:58,807 --> 00:23:00,240
"what was the cause of it?"

623
00:23:00,240 --> 00:23:02,840
And today, we get the cause
in terms of this service

624
00:23:03,850 --> 00:23:05,880
is the one that's spending a lot of money,

625
00:23:05,880 --> 00:23:07,260
but what we don't get is a context

